
[1]althea

   ALTHE'A, n. [Gr. to heal.]

   In botany, a genus of polyandrian monadelphs, of several species;
   called in English marsh-mallow.

   The common species has a perennial root, and an annual stalk rising
   four or five feet. It abounds with mucilage, and is used as an
   emollient.
